column1: This table is field data collected in the K1B watershed of Kings Creek in the Konza Biological Station near Manhattan, Kansas
This data set was created by George Allen and Arik Tashie by pacing along streams and taking wetted stream width measurements every ~5 meters with a tape measure
This data was collected to determine the distribution of stream widths in headwater catchments.

column2: Internal and external stream segments usually seperated by nodes. Order is arbitrary
We either paced upstream or downstream
Raw width measurements taken in inches
Estimated percentage of the streams that were not flowing due to sandbars, rocks, vegetation, or other material at the surface of the stream

column3: divine measurement - width visually estimated (only done a few times in Konza where poison ivy was too dense to measure)
width measured by laser range finder (in meters)

column2: name of person pacing and taking width measurements
approximate upstream accumulation area in square meters

column6: paces_run4

column2: runs 1,2,3 were done in a 1st order stream
runs 4,5,6 were done in a 3rd order stream
